# URL State — use nuqs

Whenever a client component needs to sync state with a URL search parameter, use `nuqs` instead of manually composing URLs with `useSearchParams` + `useRouter` + `usePathname`.

## Pattern

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — manual URL state
import { usePathname, useRouter, useSearchParams } from "next/navigation"

const searchParams = useSearchParams()
const pathname = usePathname()
const router = useRouter()
const tab = searchParams.get("tab") ?? "paper"

function handleChange(v: string) {
  const params = new URLSearchParams(searchParams.toString())
  params.set("tab", v)
  router.replace(`${pathname}?${params.toString()}`)
}

// ✅ GOOD — nuqs
import { useQueryState, parseAsString } from "nuqs"

const [tab, setTab] = useQueryState("tab", parseAsString.withDefault("paper"))
```

## Rules

- Import from `"nuqs"` — the `NuqsAdapter` is already mounted in `providers.tsx`
- Prefer `parseAsString`, `parseAsInteger`, `parseAsBoolean`, `parseAsStringEnum` etc. over raw string parsing
- Use `.withDefault(...)` to avoid `null` returns
- For multiple related params, use `useQueryStates` with a params object
- `shallow: true` (default) means no server round-trip — fine for UI state like tabs, filters, pagination
- Set `shallow: false` only when the server needs to know (e.g. SSR-dependent data)
